1.  Open Arduino IDE and install these libraries:
   - Go to Tools > Manage Libraries... (or press Ctrl + Shift + I)
   - Search for and install these libraries:
     - PubSubClient
     - ArduinoJson
     - DHT sensor library by Adafruit
     - Adafruit Unified Sensor
     - NTPClient

2. Configure your board:
   - Go to Tools > Board and select "NodeMCU 1.0 (ESP-12E Module)"
   - Set the upload speed to 115200 (Tools > Upload Speed)
   - Select the correct COM port (Tools > Port)

3. Copy the IndoorGardenController.ino code into a new sketch:
   - Go to File > New Sketch
   - Copy and paste the code
   - Save it with a name (e.g., "IndoorGardenController")

4. Before uploading, make sure to update these configuration values:
   - // WiFi Configuration
     const char* WIFI_SSID = "YOUR_WIFI_SSID";        // Your WiFi name
     const char* WIFI_PASSWORD = "YOUR_WIFI_PASSWORD"; // Your WiFi password

   - // MQTT Configuration
     const char* MQTT_SERVER = "d55d1972759041bf83d36d8d821741ab.s1.eu.hivemq.cloud";
     const int MQTT_PORT = 8883;
     const char* MQTT_USER = "indoor_garden_system";
     const char* MQTT_PASSWORD = "Hero4433>test43";

5. Verify your pin connections match the defined pins:
   - // Pin Definitions
     #define DHT_PIN D4              // DHT22 data pin
     #define MOISTURE_SENSOR_PIN A0  // Soil moisture sensor
     #define FAN_PIN D1             // Fan relay
     #define PUMP_PIN D2            // Pump relay
     #define LIGHT_PIN D3           // Light relay
     #define FERTILIZER_PIN D5      // Fertilizer pump relay

6. Then you can compile and upload the code to your ESP8266 using the Arduino IDE. The functionality will be exactly the same as with PlatformIO.